{
  "texts": [
    "The rise of scientific journals in the seventeenth century, the establishment of the peer review process in the eighteenth century, and the professionalization of science in the nineteenth century are all examples of how technology and institutional frameworks have shaped the role of the individual author.",
    "By the mid-twentieth century, the increasing complexity of scientific research often necessitated collaboration.",
    "But this new development came with some challenges.",
    "Namely, Wray (2006) explored the implications of collaborative research on scientific authorship and accountability.",
    "Within this work, Wray (2006) discussed two main concerns: first, collaborative research can reduce scientists' motivation due to concerns over receiving adequate credit, leading to tension and potentially discouraging participation in such projects."
  ]
}